The start symbol S has only three productions:

1. S → NT158 NT182  
   NT158 → 't15'  
   ⇒ Every string generated via this rule begins with t15.

2. S → NT56 NT75  
   NT56 → NT114 NT112  
   NT114 → NT21 NT12  
   NT21 → 't22'  
   ⇒ Every string generated via this rule begins with t22.

3. S → NT49 NT79  
   NT79 → 't5' | 't2'  
   ⇒ Every string generated via this rule ends with either t5 or t2 (because NT79 is a single-terminal non-terminal).

The string to be checked begins with t4 and ends with t0.

• It cannot be produced via rule 1, because such strings must begin with t15.  
• It cannot be produced via rule 2, because such strings must begin with t22.  
• It cannot be produced via rule 3, because such strings must end with t5 or t2.

Since none of the possible first-step productions of S can yield a string that both starts with t4 and ends with t0, the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol S has only three possible productions:

1. S → NT158 NT182  
   NT158 produces the single terminal t15, so every sentence generated by this alternative must begin with t15.  
   (Our string begins with t8 → impossible.)

2. S → NT56 NT75  
   NT56 → NT114 NT112 and NT114 → NT21 NT12 with NT21 → t22.  
   Thus every sentence produced by this alternative must begin with t22.  
   (Our string begins with t8 → impossible.)

3. S → NT49 NT79  
   The first symbol of the sentence must come from NT49.

   • NT49 can produce the terminal t6 directly (NT49 → 't6').  
     (Our string begins with t8 → impossible.)

   • NT49 → NT45 NT155, but a detailed inspection of every derivation of NT45 shows its first terminal can be t22, t21, t18, t16, t14, t10, t6, t5, or t23 – never t8.  
     (So this path cannot start the string with t8.)

   • NT49 → NT156 NT100 and NT156 → NT128 NT101 with NT128 → t8.  
     This is the only way NT49 can begin with t8.  
     In this case the second token of the sentence must be the first token produced by NT101.  
     NT101 can derive only t15, t21, or t4 (directly or via NT185 NT139).  
     None of these match the second token of the given string, which is t22.  

   Therefore even the sole NT49-based possibility that begins with t8 fails on the very next symbol.

Since none of the three productions for S can yield a sentence starting with the required prefix t8 t22, the provided string cannot be generated by the grammar.

The start symbol S can expand in only three ways:

1. S → NT158 NT182  
   – NT158 can generate only the single terminal t15, so any string derived this way must begin with t15.  
   – Our string begins with t21, so this alternative is impossible.

2. S → NT56 NT75  
   – Whatever NT75 produces must form the final part of the string.  
   – NT75 has exactly the two CNF productions  
        NT75 → NT177 NT126 ( ⇒ one token t10 / t23 followed by t3 )  
        NT75 → NT131 NT128 ( ⇒ one token t4 / t6 followed by t8 )  
     hence NT75 can generate only a two-token suffix, which must be one of  
        (t10 t3), (t23 t3), (t4 t8), (t6 t8).  
   – The last two tokens of the given string are (t23 t1), which is not among these possibilities.  
   – Therefore this alternative is impossible.

3. S → NT49 NT79  
   – NT79 can generate only the single terminal t5 or t2, so any string derived this way must end with t5 or t2.  
   – Our string ends with t1, so this alternative is impossible.

Since all possible expansions of S conflict with the given string, the grammar cannot generate the string.

The start symbol S can begin a derivation in only three ways:

1. S → NT158 NT182  
   NT158 produces the single terminal t15.  
   So this rule would make the first word of the sentence t15 (which matches the string), leaving the remaining 35 words to be generated by NT182.  
   However  
   • NT182 → NT202 NT113 would force the last word of the remainder to be t25 (it is t1).  
   • NT182 → NT157 NT107 requires NT157.  
     – NT157 → 't19' would make the second word t19 (it is t3).  
     – NT157 → NT183 NT209 forces the final word of the remainder to be t11 (there is no t11 at all).  
   Hence NT182 cannot generate the 35-word tail, so this first start rule fails.

2. S → NT56 NT75  
   NT56 → NT114 NT112 and NT114 → NT21 NT12, so the very first word produced must be t22, not t15.  
   Therefore this rule cannot match the given string.

3. S → NT49 NT79  
   NT79 → 't5', so the sentence would have to end with t5, but the given string ends with t1.  
   Hence this rule also fails.

Since every possible initial production for S is incompatible with the string, the grammar cannot generate the string.

The start symbol S has only three possible productions:

1. S → NT158 NT182  
   NT158 ⇒ 't15' – so any string derived this way begins with t15, not with the required first
   symbol t14.

2. S → NT56 NT75  
   NT56 ⇒ NT114 NT112 ⇒ NT21 NT12 … and NT21 ⇒ 't22'.  
   Hence every string from this branch starts with t22, not t14.

3. S → NT49 NT79  
   NT49 can start with t14, but only in the derivation  
        NT49 ⇒ NT45 NT155  
        NT45 ⇒ NT51 NT210  
        NT51 ⇒ 't14'  
   In this case the very next symbol is produced by NT210:  
        NT210 ⇒ NT133 NT182 ⇒ NT187 NT100 …  
        NT187 can yield only 't8' or 't11', so the second symbol would have to be t8 or t11.  
   It can never be the required t7.

Therefore none of the three possibilities for S can generate a string whose first two
symbols are t14 t7, and the given 38-symbol string cannot be produced by the grammar.

The start symbol S has only three productions:

1. S → NT158 NT182  
   NT158 produces exactly the single terminal t15, so t15 would have to be the very first symbol of the string. The given string starts with t21, so this production cannot be used.

2. S → NT56 NT75  
   NT75 can only be expanded as  
   • NT177 NT126 → (t10 t3) or (t23 t3)  
   • NT131 NT128 → (t4 t8) or (t6 t8)  
   i.e. NT75 always yields exactly two terminals, and those two terminals must be one of the four pairs above. Therefore, the overall string would have to end with one of those pairs. The actual string ends with “t7 t9”, so this production cannot generate the string either.

3. S → NT49 NT79  
   NT79 produces only the single terminal t5, so the string would have to end with t5. It ends with t9, so this production is impossible as well.

Since none of the three possible first-level derivations from S can match the required shape of the given 50-symbol string, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

The only non-terminals that can produce the terminal ‘t16’ are

 NT163 → ‘t16’ and NT7 → ‘t16’.

For the given string the first symbol is ‘t16’, so in any derivation the leftmost
token must come from one of these two non-terminals.

1. If the first token is produced by NT7, some higher rule must contain NT7 as its
leftmost child (P → NT7 …).  
   The grammar contains no production whose right-hand side starts with NT7, so
   NT7 can never be the first symbol generated by the grammar.  
   Hence NT7 cannot be the source of the initial ‘t16’.

2. Therefore the first token must come from NT163.  
   NT163 can appear as the left component only in the following rules:  

  NT154 → NT163 NT122  
  NT55 → NT163 NT18  
  NT200 → NT163 NT194  

   Consequently, the second token of the derivation must be the first token
   generated by NT122, NT18 or NT194, respectively.

   • NT122 → ‘t11’ | ‘t21’ | NT187 NT101  (first token ‘t11’ or ‘t21’)  
   • NT18  → ‘t5’  | NT31 NT147       (first token ‘t5’ or ‘t10’)  
   • NT194 → NT161 NT70 → NT115 NT113 … → NT118 … → NT178 … → ‘t24’

   So, if the first token is ‘t16’, the second token can only be
   ‘t11’, ‘t21’, ‘t5’, ‘t10’ or ‘t24’.

   In the string we have to analyse the second token is ‘t2’.

Since ‘t2’ is not among the possible tokens that can follow an initial ‘t16’,
no derivation starting with ‘t16’ can continue to produce the given string.
Because ‘t16’ must be the first symbol, the string cannot be generated by the
grammar.

Therefore the provided string is not in the language.
